Here are a few ways to achieve a "slightly warmer" background tint, depending on your tech stack (CSS, React Native, Flutter, etc.).

### Option 1: Standard CSS / Web
The most robust way to add warmth without washing out the content is using a **semi-transparent overlay** or a **background-blend**.

**Method A: Semi-transparent Overlay (Recommended)**
This keeps your text and album art perfectly readable while tinting the background.

```css
.now-playing-screen {
  /* Base dark background */
  background-color: #121212;

  /* The warm tint overlay */
  position: relative;
  overflow: hidden;
}

.now-playing-screen::before {
  content: "";
  position: absolute;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  bottom: 0;

  /* Warm gradient: subtle orange/amber to transparent */
  background: linear-gradient(
    135deg, 
    rgba(255, 140, 65, 0.15) 0%, 
    rgba(255, 140, 65, 0.05) 100%
  );

  /* Ensure the overlay sits behind content but above base bg */
  z-index: 0;
  pointer-events: none;
}

.now-playing-screen > * {
  position: relative;
  z-index: 1;
}
```

**Method B: CSS `mix-blend-mode` (Modern)**
If you want the warmth to interact with existing background images:

```css
.now-playing-screen {
  background-color: #1a1a1a;
  /* Apply a warm color with low opacity */
  background-image: radial-gradient(circle at top right, rgba(255, 180, 100, 0.3), transparent 70%);
  mix-blend-mode: screen; /* Lightens and warms */
}
```

